rw_comment: As a vegetarian, the only thing I've had at Bui's is a eggsalad sandwich.  It was kind of plain, but it's close to my side of campus and there's never a long line.

The chicken kabab sandwich was much better than I expected.  The kabab itself was delicious, but the sauce kind of drowned out the taste a bit.  Nevertheless, Casablanca is a solid option for Mediterranean food, particularly non-vegetarian.

Moderate quality Chinese food at low prices.  The highlight of this truck is definitely its prices.  Service is mediocre at best--so don't expect a friendly greeting or a \have a good day\".  When ordering during peak lunch/dinner hours (noon/6pm)
rw_overall: it helps to call ahead of time so your food is ready when you get there."

rw_comment: Friendliest food truck guy on campus.  Highly customizeable so thats always good.  Sometimes there's a big line.
Great breakfast sandwiches

Rosa's is absolutely amazing.  The food is full of flavor and it is close to my classes.  Strongly recommended for lunch, but try to go outside of the rush hours of 11-1.  Proprietor is very friendly and will remember your favorite food after a few visits.
It's all the way at DRL but its the best mexican food truck.
Good choice for breakfast before or after math.
The food is okay but its quite convenient for Hi-rise dwellers.
For the money you pay ($1.50 starting price), Frita's cannot be beat.  I started getting sandwiches here before 9am class freshman year, and I would strongly recommend it to everyone else.

I always go to Le Ahn's on my way to the subway station on 37th street.  It is fast and cheap chinese food.  Everything is topped with gravy and tastes like every other normal Chinese restaurant.  Never a long line.

I've only been to this truck once, but the food was mediocre at best and was very messy.  I might review again if I eat there again, but the line is always long around lunch time so I never get the chance.
I only ate here once and there's a reason why.
Second best grilled chicken sandwich on campus, IMO, but it is much more expensive.  Go to Khan's unless you REALLY want Hemo's sauce.

After waiting 20 minutes for food on a cold February day, almost anything would taste good.  While the price is unbeatable for the quantity, the overall experience is not something I would choose to repeat.
Typical americanized- chinese food.  Kinda outta the way because its on the other side of spruce.

Going to 40th street is usually not desirable, but to get one of Rami's falafels I will make the trip every time.  A full 50 cents cheaper than Magic Carpet, you get a bigger pita filled with falafel and veggies.  And they guy who works there (his name is not Rami) is one of the nicest food truck owners around.
Probably the best food cart on campus, fastest service and the best chinese food for sure.
Good food if you want something very spicy.  The wait is a little long, but you can usually watch America's Funniest Home Videos while you are waiting.

Crepewalk gives you a lot of food, a lot of customization, and a lot of conversation with a single visit.  Prices are very low and the proprietor is very friendly.  Only problem is that food takes a while to get and orders sometimes get messed up, but the friendliness compensates for both.  Strongly recommended.
Very fast service, but that's because all the food tastes exactly the same.  Good if you are in a rush.

Better than MexiPhilly and in a very convenient location, Lucky's produces some of the best burritos on campus.  Just like MexiPhilly, the prices are quite reasonable, but there is sometimes a long line around lunchtime.
Best burrito I have had on campus, but DAMN was it a long wait.
I always wondered why there was never a line in front of this truck.  Then I found out why.
Burritos are very good and you get a dollar off for ordering veggie ($5 burrito rather than $6).  It's a bit out of the way, but generally worth it.  Also, visit their restaurant at 69th Street.

The food tasted good, no problems there.  The problem is the time it takes for the food to be made.  I was first in line, and it took 10 minutes to get my food.  People that ordered on the phone all got their food before me so maybe I should have done that.  The prices are pretty good, too.
The chicken salad is decent, and I have heard great things about the spaghetti.  I will definitely be making another trip.
Magic Carpet is absolutely delicious and has a large variety of food, all vegetarian.  The lines can sometimes be kind of long, but each person can get their order in about a minute.
The chicken platter is pretty good but everything is a bit pricy.

While Kim's offers typical Chinese food and is almost always open, the magic lies in the dishes you may not have heard of before.  I ordered a Veg Lo Mein and it was perfectly adequate, but ordering the Kung Pao Tofu was a life-changing experience.  It is filling and has large portions, and the flavor is unmatched amongst food trucks on campus.
Freshest ingredients on campus. Everything on the menu is good.
Food was mediocre, and the line moved quickly even though it was long.
This foodtruck doesn't even charge extra for putting only certain types for fruits! It's great! highly recommended!

Great food, I go to Hemo's everyday because of the reliable service, the friendliness of the proprietor, and the excellent Hemo sauce. It's just as good as the one on 37th and Spruce, without the long lines.
They are friendly but the food is not that good and usually messy, so you have to eat, then go wash yourself before going anywhere else. Not worth it unless for the Magic Meatballs...
Khan is like my best buddy! You just have to talk about Pakistani politics with him and he opens up. For real. Nevertheless his food is good. \Oaanions

I'm a huge fan of this truck. While it may not get the same attention as its neighbor, the food is delicious, and the Friendliness is beyond compare. The hot sauce is out of this world too. Made with real Habaneros!

He only appears unfriendly because of the language barrier.  But if your try to talk to him he is quite nice.  He just gets bothered by people who dont respond promptly when he asks them to order.

But grilled chicken is damn good.  If you go there when there is less rush you can expect to get out quickly, but since he is a one man operation he gets bogged down for up to 15 - 20 minute waits during rush.  plan ahead.

Those of you who are reviewing this down have probably only went there once and probably ordered the wrong thing.

This food truck is hands down the best middle-eastern food truck on campus.

Things you need to try, grilled chicken platter, kafta kabob platter, falafel sandwhiches.  I like getting the platters with hot sauce and onions and the sandwhiches with \everything.\"

rw_id: Aside from this the friendliness and speed is damn good
ft_id: only problem can be location (unless you live in the high rises
you will get a delicious filling meal for cheap $."

rw_comment: Lamb shawarma platter. $5. Call ahead though.

These guys get to know you, and come on, how can you beat a $3 lunch that fills?

extra hemo sauce please.

I have never been to this cart.  Why am I reviewing it, you may ask?  Because IT'S NEVER THERE.  Seriously, I don't know how the owner manages to leave his shack there year-round when he is never working.

They used to have the best steaks around but this year they haven't been as good.  Maybe it's because they package them too quickly (I preferred the Styrofoam containers).  Over all they are still pretty good
Nothing different than any other fruit trucks, but very close to engineering!

The best truck on campus.  Every morning I walk by a long line at Bui to get my bacon (or ham, or sausage) egg and cheese at Steak Queen and I can only ask myself Why?  Somehow, the prices at Steak Queen are the same (or less) than Bui, yet Steak Queen uses 4 eggs and a generous serving of meat while Bui uses, from my estimation, about 1/2 egg and one strip of bacon.
Can't beat a delicious and hearty meal for as low as $2.25, but the truck never seems to be there when I want or need it most.
Not as good as MexiCali, but very convenient location, and friendly service.  The guy uses the same gloved hands to handle money and your food, which has kind of an ick factor.
So overrated. Hemo's sauce is good but I couldn't eat it every day..
Going to a Mexican truck that is not Tacos Don Memo is wrong.
Best food on campus. No joke, if someone offered me a meal at Tacos Don Memo and a meal at White Dog Cafe, I would take Tacos Don Memo in a second.
Meanest man on campus serves very hit or miss Indian food. Why doesn't someone open a good place up and blow him out of the water?
best breakfast sandwiches

BEST CHINESE FOOD ON CAMPUS in terms of noodles, and for engineers, CONVENIENT location
That guy tho.... man, PMS, anyone?

burrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrritos!

The men who work here have provided a new reason to love life. I cried tears of joy when I first ate from this food truck. It's almost blasphemy to eat Mexican anywhere else...
I definitely think this is one of the best Chinese food carts on campus.  They're definitely slow as hell, but it's right next to Huntsman and their food is awesome.  Definitely worth the wait.
Grilled Chicken! Enough said.  Takes a little longer than a Hemo's grilled chicken but he puts some great spices on it.

Had a really good Jamaican Jerk Chicken Sandwich here.  Was pricey ($5.50) but huge - lots and lots of pieces of real chicken breast (not the processed chicken like at Hemo's) and really good jerk sauce.
Hands down the best Chicken Lo Mein on campus.  Better than Kim's, better than Yue Kee, it's delicious (and cheap).

The first time I ordered from Yue Kee, I waited 30 minutes and left never having picked up my food.  I went back to try it today and it was actually faster than KoJa.  The Eggplant & Tofu I had was typical of most Americanized-Chinese food, so if there is no line I would recommend it.
While not Pod-level quality of sushi, you can't argue with a solid, mixed nigiri box - that comes with a salad and a full tekka maki - that's only $6.25.

The trick with George's truck is to become more of a regular. Even if you only eat there once a week, the staff will get to know you, and your order. If you can get there at an off-time (like, 11), you'll do even better.

I had 10 minutes to eat (including travel) so I called and placed my order.  The owner was very abrupt on the phone, but understood my order and made the food quickly.  I like that he puts the ketchup & hot sauce on the eggs while they're still on the stove, so that it is also heated up.  Recommended.
I am Asian and have been craving good, cheap noodles while at school.  KoJa's chicken noodle platter is delicious and very spicy, just the way I like it.  The portions are also very generous.

The food is absolutely wonderful and the two women who run it are very friendly.  Try the falafels, lamb shawirma, chicken shawirma, and kefta platters.  Make sure to call it because the food takes about 8 minutes to make (1 platter).  My only complaint would be the small portions.  I'm a hungry guy so two sandwiches are minimum.
Definitely order one of the platters. If you eat from lunch trucks as often as I do, sandwiches and chinese food gets old but this hasn't yet.

So this truck is sort of out of the way from the main campus. Some general advice: never let the lunch truck people think you are a new customer they will rip you off. This happened to me here but otherwise I really liked the food although it was a tad expensive
Love this truck, the sandwiches are great.
I usually get one of the rice platters or egg sandwich (cheapest one on campus). It's standard stuff but it is conveniently located, cheap, and quick.

Really great dishes here but expect long lines so call ahead. I go for the general tso chicken, and garlic chicken. there are also some secret dishes but you have to know chinese to order them they are really good.
I don't know why this is rated so poorly. I have been there a couple times, huge portions, delicious, and very spicy as I like it.
Why does nobody know about this place? Quickest meal on campus, every time. Not only is there never anyone on line (what line?), the service is extremely fast. If the cart had a \Subway\" sign on it
rw_quality: but the hoagies taste nearly the same. This place needs more attention."

rw_comment: Bui's is great. The people there are always nice and tend to remember your order if you get it more than once in a row. Perfect speed and portability if you are heading to a big lecture around 11. Make sure that when they ask you if you want salt, pepper, and ketchup, you say \Yes
rw_speed: \" if you like that delicious Vietnamese  rooster sauce. Wonderful on Bacon

rw_comment: i've eaten there quite a lot. there are much better choices out there. there's something about their chicken that i can't quite place my finger on -- i think there's a lot of air in it. it's really not as much chicken as you think it is. i'm always really hungry after eating hemo's, even when it's only 1 hour later, and this doesn't happen to me when i eat an identical meal at khan's food cart (across from it). plus, they charge for every single condiment that you add. there are better choices out there -- clearly, this food cart is overrated.

Call ahead to avoid the lines. Although their orders are a little more expensive than the other food carts, the amount and quality of food is worth it. The woman who takes your orders is really friendly. One time when my friends and I ordered during the winter, we were waiting outside in the cold for a long time. She offered us complimentary green teas to warm us up! No one else has done that.

Even though almost all of the food trucks increased their prices by 25 cents as of this year (Yue Kee is no exception), this place is still really good. The reason that they're slow is because they cook it for you in their giant wok. This is why it tastes better than the other Chinese food carts. If you've ever watched them, they scrub the wok clean every time in between dishes. I don't understand the editors' negative review of this food truck. Call ahead if you want to avoid a line. If the lady says 5 minutes, go there after 10. If she says 10 minutes, go there after 20. If she says 15 minutes, go there after 30. And so forth. Just double everything. If she ever says 25 minutes, go there about an hour later.  The prices are good, and the amount of food that you get is awesome. My personal favorite is beef chow fun. They might come off as unfriendly, and I can certainly understand why. They've been in that same location for over 20 years now. If you speak mandarin or cantonese, she does seem a bit friendlier. Just watch out for when her son is handing the food out -- he never remembers your fortune cookie.
They're really fast, and they offer really good quality food. The couple is really friendly, and the choices are really yummy.

Awesome prices! This is the only food cart that hasn't increased his prices in the past year. The grilled chicken is my favorite, and he doesn't charge for extra toppings. He may seem unfriendly, as the other guy said, but I think it's because of the language barrier. This is one of my favorite food carts, and definitely one of the most underrated ones on campus.

Lucky's burritos are bigger and better than other burrito food carts and won't fall apart if you try to eat them on the run. The chicken they use is not shredded, but is actually in intact slices of breast meat, which makes it much tastier than mexiphilly.

While the prices are pretty high for a food truck, KoJa gives you a decently large amount of food. Granted, a lot of it is rice/vegetables, but it'll fill you up. The beef bulgogi was really doused in sauce and lacking in beef. Also, the TV was missing today!

This truck is very average in most respects except that it serves fairly quickly and is the only truck I have found that serves Spaghetti.  The dish was large and cost about $3.  Worth trying at least once.

This truck is one of the few with a proprietor who is always smiling.  Highly recommended.  Strict vegetarians beware, the marinara sauce all comes from the same vat as the meatballs even if you order a veggie dish.

This is a cart I had been addicted to for a long time. Some of my favorites include the Meatball sandwich with provolone and Parmesan, or the sweat Italian sausage or the Hot Roast Beef. Everything is delicious, and there is hardly ever a line. Very friendly guy too.
Great food, wonderful service.  I'll walk from Charles Addams just for a burrito.
The egg sandwiches on a bagel or roll are great here, especially the Pork Roll Egg and Cheese.  The coffee is surprisingly good as well and much cheaper than the Starbucks across the street.
Bui's is the best by far. My favorites are the sausage egg and cheese, turkey hoagie with everything, and double cheeseburger with everything. hot sauce is a must...delicious! friendly owners!

Found this truck one day when I had only 4 bucks and thought I couldn't get anything good and filling for that little cash - boy was I wrong.
Love the bacon double cheeseburgers!
Word of caution: the hot sauce is really, really hot. You'll need a drink. And maybe two.
spaghetti with sausage is amazing

This is the best Middle Eastern food I've had in a long time!  I am not sure why people say the portions are small, because I am a big eater and their platters definately fill me up!

Fast Service, great price, I would definitely recommend!
Awesomeness. Not entirely sure why you'd eat anywhere else. Best Chinese food like anywhere.
Good jerk chicken, candied yams were excellent.  The food takes a while to come out and even if you were to order from a phone the people who work their have unintelligible accents.
This cart would be good, if it wasn't so expensive for so little.  Don't bother eating here you will be hungry again in a half hour.
good cheesesteaks, i recommend either meatbull sub or Mr. Bui's special.  mrs bui = bangable

The line was pretty long and they take a bit of time to get your order ready, but their platters come with a ton of food.  The yams and macaroni and cheese are excellent but prices are a bit high.  Then again, considering the amount of food you are getting, it's definitely worth it.

Owners of the truck are very friendly, and prices are pretty low.  I hear they had excellent breakfast sandwiches and after going, I have to agree.  Prices were really low, and the rolls were pretty big.

Amazing prices.  You can get a (great!) chicken sandwich, pretzel, and any juice/soda for $5.  So   awesome.  And the chicken really is fantastic--so much better than Hemo's oddly airy stuff.  If only Hemo's sauce could be put on Khan's chicken....hm.  Get the chicken sandwich with the sweet peppers and onions.  Forget the cheese.  Delicious.
On the slow side, but TOTALLY worth it.  Unfortunately, they're not open for the summer, but apparently they have a restaurant in Upper Darby...

Yes: Call ahead. 
Yes: Add some time onto what she says (usually add 10-15 minutes to whatever she says). It's *not* double the time like someone else said. If she tells you 20 minutes and you go 40 minutes later you will get there substantially after it was ready and end up with soggier rice. 
Yes: get the orange chicken, the spicy triple delight etc.  
Yes: food is made to order, very hot/fresh when you pick it up; it's not just sitting in a warming tub for hours like the other asian carts.
Yes: Open late, and at strange hours. Get food to order ahead when you get out of a late class or are craving food cart nutrition on a Saturday.
 
No: the cart owners do not perform fellatio  on you, but i wouldn't say they are mean, more business-like. 
No: do not try to get it if you're in a rush, e.g. on your way to class. But really, who wants a huge thing of chinese food on your way to class?

You'll have to wait, but boy is it worth it!  Marinated meat, fresh vegetables, and an amazing hot sauce that's made daily. Why get guacamole from other burrito joints when you can go to Tacos Don Memo and they will cut open a fresh avocado and put it on your burrito (for no extra charge, mind you).  The burritos are huge and will put a smile on your face.  If you think you know burritos, you don't know anything until you try this place.
FYI, apparently the Don Memo restaurant is at 57 Garrett Rd in Upper Darby (block from 69th Street terminal)... if the food is half as good as from the cart on campus, it's totally worth the trip!!

Overall, Magic Carpet has great vegetarian food.  The chefs know exactly what they're doing and will not hesitate to correct your mistakes (like asking for tahini and tzatziki sauce on the same dish).  Strongly recommended if you have the time to wait in line.  Don't worry, it moves faster than you'd expect.

I want to correct my initial review by noting that the food here is amazing if you do not order the Falafel.  Yes, it seems insane to order anything else from a place called Magic Carpet, but trust me.  Every other dish is crème brûlée to the falafel's Edy's Ice Cream.  

The woman is especially friendly at this Magic Carpet and always encourages new customers to use a fork to eat the pitas she prepares.  Warning: obey her every word.

It's been a couple of years since I last partook of George's, but as I recall the sausage and egg and chess on a long roll for $2.50 was unbeatable both taste- and pricewise.  I'm guessing the price has gone up since, but I bet it's still a good value if it's only $3.00 or so now.  Also, George and his clan are hugely friendly.
i've had good falafal all over the globe and this place is satisfying and delicious. the owner is a delight. can't beat it for the price

As a California transplant, I have to say that this is probably the best Mexican food I've found on this coast.  Only get the Torta if you are ready for a great food experience and the largest food coma you've ever had.

We LOVE Double Dragon! Steamed dumplings take a bit of time to prepare but always worth the wait, esp with the garlicky brown gravy. Also Pretty Good is the fried rice and the noodles. The girls are sweet and the bottled drinks are always cold and only $1.00.  Our visits are infrequent (we come to HUP about 5 times per year). Double D takes the sting out of going to the doctor!!

The fruit, while fresh, is not always ripe and so not as sweet and juicy as I like. It's usually cool to cold (which is a must) so it's acceptable. NEW! They now offer smoothies which are actually pretty good.
For HUP & surrounding area really good & reasonable food can be found here. Steamed dumplings are the best! The only downfall is the line at lunch. Worth the wait if you have the time.
Hey, It's hard enough to get a decent vegy meal that has more flavor than a romain salad. Check out the lasagna...it's real!

Fast, not fancy-- almost TOO much food for the money..

Really nice lady, she does remember your choices and laughs when I get wild and crazy and order medium instead of mild on my burrito.

The food is ok, nothing special. However, the food takes wayyyy too long. Even when the line is short, don't be deceived. Unless you order a hotdog, you're still guaranteed to be waiting for awhile. And even if he recognizes regulars, Khan doesn't give a hoot about them. Me and my roommates went every other day before our morning classes for two semesters and he would give us change in two dimes and a nickel (even when he clearly had quarters). He also uses Sriracha sauce (that red bottle of hot sauce) which used to be fine until he started diluting it with water. Are you serious? And even though I went so often, when I would walk by with Hemo's he'd stare me down and next time would give me beef for that. Unacceptable that he expects that I eat at Kahns every time.

Tacos Don Memo is a great food truck.  The food is delicious and the ingredients are all fresh.
I really like the pastor tacos, so if you eat pork, try them.
Don Memo restaurant just opened too.  It's located one block from 69th street (on garrett road)
Just 15-20 minutes from university city.
BYOB...
Kim's has the best orange chicken on campus!
The food tastes great, but it's slow and expensive.
Someone said this is the best Mexican food truck at Penn? There are opinions and there's flat out WRONG. Tacos Don Memo is the best Mexican truck at Penn.. El Rosa is eh.. OKAY

Maybe this place is better than MexiPhilly, which sucks.. I don't understand why people come here, honestly..
But it's still not great. Much better alternatives elsewhere on Spruce
Best food on campus. I'll eat this over Pod or White Dog any day...

All of the comparisons betweens Hemo's & Khans are a bit misguided.  Their respective grilled chicken sandwiches are two entirely different experiences.  Hemo Sauce, spinach & mushrooms makes for a fantastic sandwich. Even when busy, Hemo's moves each order along at a fast pace, and, while they're often too busy to really be friendly, they are never rude.

All of the comparisons betweens Hemo's & Khans are a bit misguided.  Their respective grilled chicken sandwiches are two entirely different experiences.  Khan's sandwich is all about the chicken.  He uses thicker chunks of well-seasoned white meat and the result is that the meat is juicier and more akin to real grilled chicken than the sauteed chicken Hemo's uses.  Khan's sandwiches are good without any condiments whatsoever, but I will agree that a Khan's sandwich with Hemo Sauce would be the best lunch on campus. The other great thing about Khan's is the generous portion size. I've never been hungry after one of his sandwiches.  Khan may sometimes seem impatient and may even seem rude, but I appreciate the fact that he doesn't suffer fools or rude customers gladly.  If you treat him with respect, you'll receive it in return, and it will be real, not some phony customer service tactic.  You may wait longer than other places because he is a solo act, but the line is usually shorter than at other trucks.

The bread isn't a perfect Philadelphia roll (non-natives won't be able to tell), but the thick juicy slices of medium-rare roast beef are a distinct plus. No line, excellent sandwiches, low prices.  Best option for hoagie on a truck and better than the Wawa across the street.

I ordered a veggie pita special without the special (it's just a drink and chips for a buck fifty extra).  The sandwich was very good, though it was a little messy as I walked to DRL.

Even though the owners were very busy making other sandwiches, they were very friendly in answering my questions about the history of the truck.

I would strongly recommend this truck if you are in the hospital area.

I've been on campus for 8 years, and this was my first food truck meal ever. Every time I go there, I vow it'll be my last time because the food tastes so terrible -- overseasoned, over-use of vinegar and soy sauce, too little rice and vegetables taste old and un-fresh -- but I keep going back because the lines at all the other trucks can get so long. Fair priced and worth it if all you want to do is fill your stomach with something that won't kill you, and you don't want to wait for it, but the description above is wrong -- the line ALWAYS is longer than 5 people during busy times because everyone thinks this place is soooo fast that they come here.
The shrimp here is amazing, and their fried foods are good, too.

To be fair, this is only based on 2 dishes I got with them because I never went back after that. I tried ordering the wok-fried stuff, but there was an overuse of vinegar both times that made it taste kind of weird.

There is only one dish you should ever get here, and that's the curry chicken with bones. It's probably the closest example to HK-style curry you can get from the foodtrucks. The mongolian beef isn't bad either, I admit.

The food isn't gooey/wrong like the other Chinese food trucks, and the variety is much greater.  Try the eggplant chicken or the chili chicken, or the maopo tofu.  Don't get discouraged by long lines--I've been in lines there that were over 20 people long and I still got my food in less than 5 minutes.
This fruit truck has the best mango slices almost all of the time. They cut them very well, at just the right ripeness, and give you a banana too. Great if you like mango.
It's like an orgasm in the mouth. Cheap and fast. Breakfast sausage egg and cheese is a favorite.
Really good stuff - get the grilled chicken sandwich from there!

A real nice place to go.  Can get busy but they churn out the food fast.  Everything on the menu is good, but I prefer the steak sandwiches and egg sandwiches.  The chicken, sausages/hot dogs, and hot roast beef are tasty too.  Meatball sandwich is the only one I wouldn't recommend (unremarkable).  Great food at a great price, I eat there often.
Tacos Don Memo is the don of all food trucks on campus and belongs on top. It's the best food on Penn's campus no doubt.
Chicken tostada every time.  Medium hot sauce.  I love this place.
Love this place. Tasty and quick - their bread has a nice outside-toasted crunch to it and their sausage, egg & cheese breakfast hoagie with special sauce is amazing!

I started getting the Mixed Cheese wrap here a few months ago.  Though the guy still doesn't remember my order, he knows that I always get whole-wheat and no mayo.  Strongly recommend the wraps as they are quite filling and very tasty for a mere $3.50.  I wouldn't bother waiting in line if there are more than three people ahead of you.

You're gonna spend a few more bucks to eat here, but its still a great value compared to eating at a restaurant (duh - its a food cart).  More importantly, you're gonna get great food, very satisfying and fresh.  I like the woman who runs the cart by the hospital, very friendly and has a good rapport with a lot of customers.

I work around the corner at Trophy Bikes, but I don't go here just because its closeby... I go here on a near daily basis because its the best food cart I've ever been to. The line can sometimes be a bit long, but it always looks worse than the actual wait time.  They cook fast and are quick to move things along and get you your food. Food quality is honestly average/above average, but very consistent. You'll keep coming back because of the fast service and of course the CHEAP prices... tip them!

I work around the corner at Trophy Bikes, and even when starving will never eat here.  At best, the food is mediocre. Typically though, this stuff is too salty, too greasy, and not passable.  Inconsistent too - the staff changes on a daily basis, so you never know how your order is gonna turn out. That, and sometimes the truck doesn't show up at all!

The burritos aren't as good as Don Memo's or Mexicali or Qdoba or Chipotle or Distrito or Taco Bell...but its worth stopping by.  I like coming here when I'm in a rush (I work around the corner at Trophy Bikes) or when I don't want to spend $7 on a big burrito. Yes, portions are generous. The menu is also fairly diverse and the staff is Mexican.

Amazing - called in my order 45 minutes early, showed up an hour later, and they didn't have it ready. Staff was super friendly and apologetic. The wait time is huge, but really, this is a testament to their end product, and of course a testament to laws of supply and demand. People wait because its worth it...so bring an ipod, a book, a friend, whatever, and enjoy the time outside.  You'll certainly enjoy the food.

I work a block away at Trophy Bikes, but even still I will go out of my way to hit up Alladin's every time. Magic Carpet has a giant and tasty menu, but portions are small and prices are big. You're not going to get the food truck value here, and you're also going to wait a long time in line. Its a nice treat, def good quality and a change-of-pace, but probably not a standby lunch spot for most discerning food truck junkies.

Having read reviews and heard talk about this cart, I was very enthusiastic to try it. Unfortunately the chicken burrito I ordered did not live up to expectations. The meat, while flavorful, was not the best quality. It was all dark meat and I had several unpleasant and chewy bites. The tomatoes were thick slices rather than diced cubes. This lead to sections of the burrito being watery and bitter. The guacamole, a featured aspect of this cart, was buried beneath the other flavors and was not readily distinguishable. 

On the plus side, the rice, beans and portion size were noticably superior to other carts in the area. 

Unfortunately at a price of $6 and with very slow service, 20 minutes when I was the only one in line, I can not recommend this cart.
I've gotten fruit a few times here. Last time I picked up a couple of nectarines and brought them home. I put them in the sink to wash them and a couple of cockroaches crawed out. Gross.
steak and chicken burritos were pretty good.  spicy warning was appreciated, but found to be unwarranted.  just spicy enough.
all this talk about hemo's...and just an average sandwich.  will go back for a breakfast sandwich to see if they can redeem themselves there.

soooo much better than the fruit cart on 34th and walnut.  this fruit cart has much riper fruit even when the fruit is out of season (like mango in february).  the lines can get long, but it's worth it.  also, it's expensive only because fruit is expensive in general--if you go to frogro and try to buy this stuff, it's much pricier.  when i lived in hill, i used to walk all the way to this cart for fruit because other places just don't compare.

Steak Queen truly is the best steak on campus!  Steak Queen is very consistent, unlike the other food trucks which are often hit-or-miss.

Don't be put off by the abruptness of Mr. & Mrs. Steak Queen...its all in the name of speed!

this man looks like the buddha! he's very quiet, but he's not mean. food is always super hot. he doesn't mess around with the spices either, and i love spicy food. mild is fairly spicy, medium is my upper limit, and spicy makes me cry.

They definitely cook fast and still have good food. Yue kee's is the only chinese food cart that is comparable in quality and their waits are about 20-40 mins. Good vegetarian options and a number of dishes where the seasoning or sauces taste different from one another (not the same old brown goo).

George's has the best sausage-egg-and-cheese sandwich anywhere.  They are the only truck that uses REAL sausage, not the ground patties used everywhere else; also, they use more eggs.  The food is delicious, generally grease-free, and best of all, the couple who run it are incredibly friendly, often throwing in free snacks for regulars.
Amazing. The dude that runs the truck is also super nice.

In my opinion, the food is great. I usually frequent their place on 60th & Haverford but i've been to the truck a few times. you have to wait a little while but it's worth it. Side's are great. recommend hot sauce on....almost anything.
Kimbab fridays never cease to amaze...

You can get dishes here that are probably the most authentic Chinese in Philly outside of Chinatown.  They're also quite tasty.  Sure, the woman has a soup-Nazi attitude but that's why you call ahead ;).

Are people seriously listing the quality as a 4 here?  Are you living under a rock?  Where are you eating that is possibly worse than here?  Stop eating there, wherever it is!  Most items taste almost exactly the same, which is bad.  The \generic gravy\" noted should be changed to \"Gross sauce\" and we'll be good to go.  Eat here only when trying to enforce your diet
rw_overall: as you will not want to finish your plate."

rw_comment: Food is almost exactly the same as the other Le Ahn, which is not a good thing.  Unless they are competing for the worst non-food court Chinese food, there is really not much point in their focus on brand distinction.  I have not tried the Bubble tea however, so they may at least be a good source of beverages.

Okay, firstly- the Chinese food here is very American style.  It's like your local chinese place in the suburbs.  However, I grew up in the suburbs and enjoy the food here a lot.  It's reasonably priced and really tasty.  I look forward to hearing their trademark \You want spicy?\"  For a quick meal
rw_overall: they're one of the best carts on campus.  My favorite dishes are the sesame chicken and spring roll
rw_quality: but they're reliable on almost all dishes."

rw_comment: I've only had one thing here but it was great. I get the shrimp and broccoli and it's fantastic! Wayy better than real le anh or le anh
Large portions, I rarely even finish the small. You should try the jerk chicken or fish...highly recommended!
Big sandwiches, low prices. Very friendly, free pretzel if you are one of the last people of the day (and they have some left over)
I've always called this cart \Asian Gentleman\" because \"Greek Lady\" used to exist in its place.  It's great
rw_overall: the guy is friendly and quick
rw_quality: and it really should have longer lines."

rw_comment:
The fried fish was way too fishy--disappointing. The candied yams were cloyingly sweet. The green beans were salty enough to make your taste buds shrivel.

However, the jerk chicken is delicious. Very succulent meat and tasty spices--I will ask for hot sauce though, next time. The potato salad is nice and cool. The collard greens were also very good.

The small was $7 which might seem steep but there's so much food that I can eat it for 2 meals.

I love this food truck. The lady is actually from Indonesia not Singapore. I love her hot sauce, I usually ordered chicken burrito and roast pepper with extra hot sauce. The sauce really kicks in. If I was really hungry, I'd go with the tostadas. They're huge! 
I've had few cravings for the burritos now that I'm no longer going to Penn. (And I haven't found the same hotsauce here in cali) :( The only thing that I don't like is she opens from 11-3. Sometime she leaves earlier than that. :( I wish she would open the business much longer.

You will not find a better breakfast sandwich on campus. 

You get a big portion for a great price, the food is consistently perfect, and if you don't have a crush on Linh after a few days there's something wrong with you.

Here's the thing, the real le anh does a few things very well and you just have to try until you find them. Their chicken pad thai is absolutely outrageous, it's 5 dollars and is worth every penny - one of the most solid finds on penn's campus.

I've been eating from this truck for almost 9 years now, and the food is always good. The staff is always friendly, and boy do they work. 
The description says they're only open for lunch, but they are there early for breakfast. 

Try a steak, egg and cheese sandwich for breakfast and you'll be telling your friends to get one too.

Kim's is always extremely fast and always great! Their Kung Pao Chicken is great as is their Kung Pao Tofu but if you ask for Kung Pao Chicken and Tofu it is AMAZING. Sauce is really good, amount of rice is great, and the tofu is good well as is their chicken. Even if it seems like there are 30 people waiting in line, don't be afraid - it'll never take more than 5 minutes

I can't complain too much because in the cold damp soggy weather, you don't wanna go too far for something to eat when you're starving, and this is conveniently right by the eng'g school, so cause of that, and cause the food was pretty good, it's a good stop for breakfast definitely!

I liked it when I first started going there at the beginning of the year, but then they started to run out of certain fruits that weren't in season.  Normally that wouldn't bother me, but other fruit carts seem to have all the fruits year round--except this one for some reason.  My main gripe was that they pretty much had no mango after october.  They probably had it again at some point later in the year, but I got my fruit elsewhere by then.

This is without a doubt one of the best food carts I've encountered on campus. I would also recommend KoJa above some of the pricier Korean restaurants in the area. The only real drawback is that there is a bit of wait. Please check this out, it is worthwhile.
I almost go there every day for lunch, and I'm still not tired of it! The food is great, the guy is quick and nice. Not much to say against

Two words: veggie. tacos. I go to Tacos Don Memo at least twice a week just to get two vegetarian tacos. Their tortillas are SO DELICIOUS, all of their ingredients are super fresh, and the guys that work there are always sweet. Couldn't ask for more.

The beef in the beef and broccoli was more grilled than cooked ala chinese people's cooking.  Although the food truck owner was fast and friendly, most of the food was undercooked rice slathered in sauce.
There are some great finds at The Real Le Anh. The chicken eggplant is absolutely delicious, as is the chicken pad thai.
Dish cost $6 and was all rice. Complete rip-off.
Can't believe I wasted 3 years on campus before discovering Kim's.

same prices as the fruit cart on 37th and spruce across the street, but not as generous in terms of what they give you.  the other fruit cart stuffs your container to capacity--and needs to use rubber bands to keep it somewhat closed.  at this one i heard the click of the plastic actually being able to close, and i knew she was being stingy.  also, gave me a hard time about asking for more non-melon.  never had that problem at the other cart.  fruit was ripe, but i'd wait at the 37th and spruce cart instead any day it's open.
I tried their food a couple of times and was horribly disappointed each time.

I only get 3 things here but that's only because they are too good to try anything else. 1. Curry (as authentic as it can get) 2. Seafood Combo (Quite tasty and the most bang for your buck. 3. Hot and Sour soup.

So far in my search for the best burrito in Philly, two places stand out: Jose's on 469 N. 10th st and Taco's Don Memo. Fresh ingredients, rice and beans done right. Excellent toppings and grilled tortilla. It's amazing to me how many other places get it so wrong. Memo does it right. Just be willing to wait for it.

The prices are cheap but the lady and the guy who works guy on sunday do not wear gloves.They don't wash their hands after they handle money either.I saw that and I walked away especially if the are making cold meat.

Waited 30 min to get served because the guy forgot the order and put some people that called in an order ahead of me.  Brags about how good his food is which is fine if it was any good.  You'll get more, better, and faster food if you just go 2 trucks down to Le Ahn's.  Did I say how annoying this guy is, yet?

Best burrito everrrrr. After reading this page, I decided to order ahead so it was ready for me when I got there. But the line wasn't long at all anyway. It's right by my work so it's pretty convenient and although the dudes aren't the friendliest, I'm not really looking for conversation with my burrito-makers.

They offer a very generous amount of food on their crepes. The older guy is the dude's dad. Although they don't wear gloves when they grab veggies from the bags, it all gets cooked I suppose -- with the exception of lettuce and tomato. Most of their crepes are at $4.75, which is slightly more than other places, but I love the food. Definitely call ahead to place your order...
One of the best on campus. $3 chicken sticks are a steal and the noodle plates can feed 3!

I love Lyn's!  I tried all the other sandwich carts on Spruce and Lyn's consistently had better quality, better portion size, and simply the best overall value.  Nothing special, nothing fancy, just delicious cheesesteaks, eggplant parm, breakfast sandwiches, et cetera.  I've never had a bad or even mildly disappointing meal there.  Try the cheesesteak with hot sauce (Sriracha) and mayonnaise \on the bun.\""
I got some shrimp fried rice hear - and it was basically steamed brown rice, sprouts and flourescent orange shrimp.  Not good.

This truck has the best greek salad anywhere. Be sure to ask for a pita with the salad. I don't care for the chicken cheesesteak of grilled chicken anything b/c they serve thier chicken very dry. I am told their meat products are tasty, but I don't eat meat, so can't say for sure.
Good cheesesteaks and very friendly.
All the food is steamed with just some brown gravy poured over it.  Gross.  Even the spring rolls are tasteless. Go to Kim's instead.  It is worth the walk.
The mixed fruit is usually pretty good, but check the banana before leaving. I got one that was all brown mush inside once.

I like the guy in this cart. He reminds me of Freddy Mercury. He is also really nice and has good breakfast and lunch. Chicken cheesesteaks are really good, as are his egg and cheesesandwaichs and tea. Plus, he will talk Pakistani politics with you.

Long line, but it moves quickly, and there's a reason everyone's going here. Try the magic meatball or the seitan grinder; either one will tempt you to become a vegetarian. Note: These \sandwiches\" are meant to be eaten at least partially with a fork.

rw_id: Dazzling variety of interesting soft drinks. You might not be able to find coke
ft_id: but there will be three varieties of birch beer."

rw_comment: I ordered sesame chicken, but it tasted like it was soaked in barbecue sauce. The fried rice was pretty bland too. I agree with the previous reviewer, it tastes a lot like Le Anh's which is also subpar.

I've heard that this is the closest truck to authentic chinese around. It's tasty and convenient, and seems somewhat healthier than most, since dishes aren't swimming in sauce and provide plenty of veggies.

This is my go-to truck. The grilled chicken special on a long roll is delicious - get it with a mix of honey mustard and mayo. I'm not a fan of their tuna, and they don't carry kaiser rolls... but no other complaints. Totally worth the wait!
I've gotten a few meat tacos in the last week, and the quality hasn't dipped at all. There have been a few people there each time, but I still got my food pretty fast and enjoyed every bite of it.

I went during lunch. Since it's at HUP, it was close to Engineering and not that far of a walk to get to.

I ordered the Tofu and Vegetables in Garlic Sauce. It was saucy and spicy, just the way I like it. 

The price was higher than most of the other Chinese food carts, but the portion was also slightly bigger, so I guess that made up for it.

I would go there again if the like at Frita's is long or if I'm craving Chinese and feeling too lazy to walk to Le Ahn's.

I absolutely love going to Magic Carpet.

I used to go there often enough and got the same thing (Foo Chow - Baked Tofu over Rice and Veggies with tahini, hot sauce, sesame seeds, soy sauce) that they know exactly what I order. The variety of lemonades and root beers still astounds me.

The proprietors are really nice. One time I forgot my wallet and the lady let me get my order anyway and pay her back later. 

A few warnings: big line (~15-20 people); slightly higher price (~5.50); not meant to eat while walking, but fairly easy to take to class.

Breakfast at Khan's is the best deal in Philadelphia. Freshly scrambled eggs, beef bacon and cheese on a long roll for $2.00! Where you going to find a deal like that? I agree with other posters that the proprietor may seem unfriendly, but he actually will crack a smile and warm up if you make an effort to connect. He sometimes even rewards friendliness with and extra slice of beef bacon on your sandwich. You may want to avoid the coffee however. Not the best, but a small price to pay for convenience. Besides your going to need an icy diet coke to cut the grease from your sandwich. Grilled chicken for lunch is tops as per the other posters. Salt, pepper, ketchup, lettuce, tomato? Be sure to know what you want before you step up or risk invoking the Wrath of Khan!!!
Best egg and cheese (when not too busy) and Italian sausage. Everything else is standard. Worst coffee on campus.
The daily specials taste great. Everything comes with vegetables (salad or tabbouleh). Chicken kabob with garlic sauce is pretty good.

The famous Hemo's chicken sandwich is indeed Penn's most popular meat-flavored sandwich. The bulk of it is composed of some sort of unidentifiable chicken product. (Granted, I ate there a few years back.)

I ordered the pierogies, and while they were good, they were incredibly expensive at $1 per pierogi and they were smaller than expected.  Didn't try the crepes, but they too are $5, so probably not worth it.
By far my favorite food cart. Amazing egg and cheese and meatball subs to die for. Talking sports with Billy is always a good time and its the type of place where they learn your name.

The few times I've been there, Khan has ALWAYS given incorrect change to people in front of me that pay with 20s. I've seen two people point it out to him and he gave them a dollar without a word or \sorry..\" as if he had been caught and he just wanted to move on. The food is very greasy and Khan himself is uncharismatic."

I ordered on foodtrux.com and my order was there waiting for me.  Amidst a busy schedule, the convenience of being able to order tasty Mexican food and have it prepared for me at the exact time I desire is a godsend.

My buddy and I ate here and we both got chicken burritos. He didn't like the chicken in his partly b/c it had a weird taste and it was shredded. I thought it tasted fine and I like the shredded, however, there wasn't enough of it. The burrito was mostly beans, which felt like a lead brick in our bellies even hours later, which could be a good thing.

I went to this cart a couple of years ago and the food was really really spicy (because I ordered spicy, go figures). 

I decided to go back to give it a fair shot. But this time the food just sucked. It was expensive (~$6) and just awful.

It was mostly rice with a little bit of the actual entree. The peas were uncooked and the paneer was chewy. The curry was very liquidy and bland and had no redeeming qualities whatsoever.

Never again will I go here.

The Grilled Chicken is good.  At some food trucks, the chicken doesn't look like real chicken - it has a weird texture, the result of using lower quality meat.  Here, the chicken looks much better, and tastes better.

rw_title: found a screw in my food
rw_comment:
This was only the second time I went to King's Wok.
The first time I had an egg foo young which was pretty tasty, just a bit too saturated with sauce, but it was still fine and that's why I decided to go back and try some other dishes.
While I was happily chewing away to my Sichuan pork and plain fried rice which both only had the taste of soy sauce, I found myself biting into something hard which first I though was a pebble. How surprised was I to find that apparently it was a screw, a rusty dirty screw....

Lyn's is popular for a reason. 
-Very low prices for breakfast sandwiches. Buis is great, but these are cheaper and around the same size.   
- Service is super friendly
-Service is fast, even considering the large lunchtime crowd

Holy crow! I thought I was the only one unlucky enough to find strange things in King's Wok's food! I am a glutton for punishment and get food from King's Wok pretty regularly because it's convenient, but twice I found little rocks in the shrimp with black bean sauce. The pork egg foo young and pork chow fun are the two faves I usually get from there now.

I have been going to this truck since 1989. The food has always been great and once the guy gets to know you, he'll throw in freebies in your meal like the aforementioned falafel ball or a small portion of the entree of the day. I'm Chinese and I find myself eating here more often than any of the Chinese food trucks. Kebby on Wednesdays and Riz Al Djaj on Thursdays are the best. If you get the chicken kabob, you will find it most excellent but you will stink up the entire classroom with your newly acquired garlic breath.

This place is a must go! The crepes are nice and thin and full of flavor.each crepe is unique, made with a lot of care and not just thrown in together. you can customize your crepes by adding or removing a few items as the cart guy is very friendly. special mention about the sweet crepes. you must have a little patience though as he takes time to make it! for first timers - go during a non rush hour when there is no one ahead in line.
Very good food for the price. try the platter with zucchini. wouldnt rate their hummus highly though. can call and place orders to pick up too.
I had the Schezwan tofu and it was awesome. For Indians, I would say it was close to Indian-chinese food that we all miss.
Great, freshly cooked tacos.  Excellent guacamole.

I'm 6'2'' and 195 lbs, and I can barely finish a meal here. Most entrees are 4.50 to 5.50, which isn't cheap but is still comparable to other trucks (KoJa, Hemos, Steak Queen...). Also, the guy isn't friendly, but he understands english well and gets you what you ask for--what more do you want? Frankly, I don't want to chitchat--I want my food! Also, service is slow, but there's rarely a line, so it's still comparable to Hemos, KoJa, and most other trucks. This is one of my top 5 (KoJa, Yue Kee, Curry on Wheels, Kahn's, Luckys)

The falafel with baba ganouj is expensive and not filling.  The proprietor was not very friendly and the falafel was not sealed well at the bottom.  I ended up eating the food over a trash can.  Perhaps, I should have just dropped the whole thing in.
Lyn's eggplant parm is sooo good. Their daughter went to Penn, so they know how to cater to Penn students.

Maybe the best authentic Mexican food in Philadelphia. I dare you to find a better taco anywhere in the city! The lines and waiting time are long for a reason--the end product is superb. Amazing food that is well worth waiting for.

Viva El Memo! Much tastier fare than you'll find at any other truck. Others are faster? Who cares? No one comes close to this taste! Go to McDonald's instead if you want fast, shitty food. Come here if you want delicious, delicious art.

Exceedingly friendly and excellent homemade hot sauce.  Tried the mushroom/pepper/spinach burrito, not going for authentic (since the owner is Indonesian) but for taste.  Decent beans & rice, nice texture from the mushrooms.  The hot sauce apparently isn't as fiery as it once was (hot should probably be called medium), but it was certainly delicious.  Planning to go again soon and try a tostada.

Everything is premade and stored in vats in the truck, so the lines are quick. However, that doesn't make up for the rubbery chicken (which tastes exactly like the chicken from Lucky's) and the watered-down sauces. The difference between a bowl and a platter is 3 tiny pieces of naan and $1.50. Also, at least for now, their menu is extremely limited - just generic \curry\" meats/veggies. The veggie options might be better
rw_quality: spend a few extra bucks and go to Sitar or Tandoor. "

rw_comment: I really enjoyed the aloo tikki masala that I had, but it was not enough for a full lunch.  If you're craving Indian food, it's definitely worth the $4 pricetag, but don't expect to have leftovers.

I've tried a couple other Indian food carts and their food is the most tasteless stuff around the Penn area. Lovash actually uses spices in their cooking, even in the rice. The portions are relatively small (Compared to the chinese food trucks), but if you're craving some indian food for one meal, its a great choice. I haven't tried their meat options, so I can't comment there, but their vegetable curries have some taste and contain assorted veggies.

I finally tried their ham/egg/cheese breakfast sandwich today after reading all the reviews and LOVED it. The bread was warm and fluffy, and all the ingredients melted together in harmony. This will definitely be one of my staples during my next few years at Penn.

The breakfast fare is among the best in the area.  The sausage/egg/cheese on the toasted roll (with a Siracha and ketchup), is a top notch sandwich for under 4 dollars.  

The cheesesteak is similarly good, at a great value.  The rolls are of great quality.

Also of note is the speed is better than most of the other food trucks, they move quickly.  In addition, I second the above point, Mrs. Bui is definitely bangable.

I just can't get enough of Ali baba's food. I can't really decide what my favorite meal is. Maybe a three-way tie between the Shish tawook (grilled chicken, tabouli and garlic sauce), the kebby platter, or the Kafta platter. Also has the best falafel in town!

Hemo's is a Penn staple, but I don't see all the fuss about it. The people who work the cart are really great - they know their regulars, and they're really friendly to everyone. Their cheesesteaks are also pretty decent, but they get pricey as you pile on the toppings. Hemo's always has the longest lines during rush hours due to its long-standing popularity with students. Try it out. But I've never felt that Hemo's food was particularly good - there are better food carts out there.

Be forewarned - their food all tastes the same. Chicken w/ Broccoli? 1 part real broccoli, 2 parts rice, 1 part synthetic all purpose meat. But the people are exceedingly friendly, and around dinner, you can get huge portions for relatively low prices. For anyone close to the lower quad gates, Le Anh can't be beat for convenience. The operating hours are great, and lines are never long. Their lo mein and spring rolls are not to be overlooked! My favorite mediocre food cart.

Review posted on my food blog:

http://munchimonster.wordpress.com/2009/10/10/legit-japanese-food-in-a-cart/
Rice was poorly cooked, bread was bland.  Entrees were nowhere near authentic.  Portions were big but it doesn't matter when the food is this bad.

finally an Indian food truck on campus that has tasty food. 
portions do not look huge but with indian food that is generally heavy - this is good enough. better off not taking the platter and paying extra $1.50 for it.
Delicious. A bit out of the way for Penn students, but if you have time it's worth it.
There are better Mexican trucks, but this one is quick and near DRL, which is convenient if you're there for class. It's a bit expensive, and I wouldn't get it if there were other options there,
The only thing that keeps this place from being a \top tier\" food truck is the bad location
rw_overall: although I love this place I find it difficult to go out of my way to get food from there.  When I lived closer to it though
rw_quality: I ate there all the time.

rw_id: Definitely anything grilled chicken (platter or sandwich) is a must.  If you are feeling something with rice
ft_id: definitely has some of the best options on campus.  And if you want any sort of quick and filling
rw_email: this is the place to go.

rw_id: Falafel and Grape leaves are pretty good too!"

rw_comment:
Some of the best food on campus, seriously.  Unfortunately due to location it is not as well frequented as it should be.

Anything grilled chicken is damn good here (platter or sandwich).

If you are feeling something with rice, can't go wrong with any of the platters.

If you want something quick and filling, but that doesn't feel light, the sandwiches are perfect for you.

Falafel and Grape leaves complement the food nicely, so seriously try it out!
Spaghetti is a unique cart offering, and is quite good (as well as plenty of food for the price). Also has the best pork roll sandwiches this side of campus.

This food is really good.  Took the time to get to know the owner, who can come off negatively, and he's a really nice guy.  Usually skip over if more than 2 people because of the wait but if I go and there's no one, I do cartwheels.  BTW- must order at least medium spicy for food to be tasty. Non spicy is really non tasty.
a great value...pretty healthy, filling, and tasty!

I don't understand the complaints about the price; George's prices are roughly a dollar less than similar carts all around campus. $2.25 for a breakfast sandwich on a Kaiser roll sounds like a pretty good deal to me.
Food is not as good as other ratings led me to think and the wait is just not worth it.

I had the Bacon and Eggs sandwhich with cheese for a mere $3. Considering I got a full footlong sandwhich, I thought it was great. The bacon was excellent, the eggs were just fine. The bread was obviously fresh.
I enjoyed their cheesesteaks, especially when it was only at $4.  I real deal that everyone should try.
GREAT burritos, very unique combinations!  You do have to wait a bit to get your burrito, and the truck isn't there a whole lot, but the best cart I have been to!

I went to le ahn expecting some decent chinese food...and i just received a load of crap.  the food was bland chicken and rice piled on with some disgusting generic gravy.  in addition to the slop i received, there was a long, distinctly black and pin straight hair in my food. it was disgusting. i went to get my money back, and the lady argued   with me! just awful go to yue kee instead!
the garbanzo beans are the best.. tastes more like an Indian dish, than mexician-but awesome!
Basically the best chicken sandwich you will find at Penn. I think some of my fellow reviewers must be mistaking Hemo's for another cart, because it is always an amazing experience. And cheap.

Out of all Chinese food trucks on Penn campus, this is by far the all-round best one. Not only is the service very fast, the food is absolutely delicious. The most notable dish is Kung Pao Chicken, which never fails to satisfy me. Have you ever asked yourself: \Where can I get a delicious
rw_quality: chinese meal that won't make me feel like crap after eating it? Well
rw_speed: this is your solution: Kung Pao Chicken at Kim's. Go for it."

rw_comment:
Gave me the runs...

Need  I say more

Probably one of my favorite trucks on campus. Breakfast sandwiches are delicious, cheap and massive. Cheesesteaks are also some of the best around, and the grilled chicken pitas/sandwiches are amazing, mostly because of their special honey mustard sauce. I don't even generally like honey mustard, but it's fantastic.
I really like this place. All the food is cooked fresh, you get a lot of it, and there is lots of variety. Only get the spicy if your tolerance is super high.

I absolutely ADORE Tacos Don Memo. I'm at this food truck at least twice a week for two spicy veggie tacos with sour cream. However, they are exceedingly slow. I ordered over the phone the other day to avoid being late for class, and asked for my two tacos to be ready by 12:45. I arrive at 12:45, they say it's coming up, and I STILL had to wait literally fifteen minutes to get my food. I may as well have just gone in person to order. Calling did no good at all (and they forgot my sour cream this time, even though I ordered it...). Anyhoo, their food is EXCELLENT, but be prepared to wait wait wait.

I agree that the Seafood combo is very tasty - love it with Pineapple.  Additional their hot and sour soup is so yummy especially on cold day.  the lady is so pleasant.  And certainly the service is quick and the food cheap for the amount that you get.

For the money you get a nice sized portion of curry and rice. Sure, the food is not spectacular Indian, but it's pretty cheap, reasonably tasty, and a pretty big size. I like very spicy food, so I'm happy that the owner will make the spiciest truck food on campus if you ask for it.

In contrast to the editor's review, I find the food to be better quality than any of the local buffets, though Indian food in Philadelphia seriously lacks. This is the best of the mediocre options on campus IMO. A better option is Kabobeesh at 42nd and Chestnut.

Downsides are the truck is slow (everything is cooked to order of course), there's no call ahead number, the owner can be gruff, and there's no naan bread option--just thick pita bread.

I've been going here for many years now. The large numbers of Chinese immigrants that flock to this truck speaks volumes for its quality and authenticity. Try ordering random things from the Chinese menu--but you might get tasty fried fish or interesting beef tendon ;)

At peak hours they get quite crowded, so either use the faded out phone number on the Chinese menu to call ahead, or come at non-peak hours. 

I think the real standouts at this truck are the garlic sauce options and shrimp options, especially shrimp and eggplant (a steal for $4), or the singapore noodles.
These prices are inaccurate; please fix them.
Their food is great. The platters are filling and the grilled chicken and fallafel are amazing. The menu that is attached on this site is wrong.

There are a bunch of Indian restaurants near Penn's campus, so why would you pick this food truck behind the gym? Put simply, its excellent value for money. All curry and rice dishes are in the $5-6 range, and make for a very substantial meal. The food quality is excellent, the dishes are flavorful, and meal portions are very decent.

Sure, the owner is a bit gruff and doesn't do anything made-to-order except for mild/medium/spicy. And yes, the service is slow (because the food is put together after you order, and there's only one cook). And there are no breads except for a thick pita-type of bread.
I think Yue Kee does a few dishes very well. As far as I can tell, they have the best ma po tofu in the city. They make a few good noodle dishes like the singapore noodle or \beijing hot noodle\".

rw_id: But then the things Americans are most likely to know and love are the things done worst or in a very mediocre way at this truck.
So at least try the ma po tofu for $3.25. If it doesn't change your life
ft_id: at least you can say you've been to this well known
so call ahead AND don't come during peak hours."

rw_comment:
There's some very good Korean food at this truck. The spicy noodle platters are my favorite. I think this truck deserves special mention for making some of the best vegetarian food on campus. The japchae bap (noodles and vegetables with rice) or tofu noodle platter are massive portions of spicy goodness.

My only complaints are that the kimchi is radish kimchi and it's very mild for Americans. Also, the rice platters use a lot of cabbage for filler, so you end up with not so much meat.

The Friday special went up to $4.50 per platter after 3pm but it's still well worth it. Oh yeah, they have Japanese food too, which is okay if you want your food a lot blander and sweeter. I don't understand the obsession with kimbap, but if pickled radish sushi is your thing, pick some up for lunch on a Friday!

The owner lady is super nice. She remembered what I liked to order even after I had been away from campus for a year! Cups of tea while waiting on a super cold winter can just brighten your day.

FWIW, the owner goes by Sam. Rami is one of his family members. Was it his niece? I can't remember, it's been a few years. Overall he's a funny guy with all sorts of Rami-isms like: \You want drink?\" \"How about ice cold beer?\" \"What can I get for nice young lady?\"

ft_id: I've traveled to many places in the world and I still think Rami's has the best falafel on the planet. They're Lebanese style with crispy exterior
rw_owner: nicely spiced filling with slightly grainy texture. Awesome.

rw_id: Why mess around? I just get the falafel platter to have 6 of them all to myself.
Overall I think the middle eastern food here is the best in the city. Amazing (depressing?) that it is from a food truck. It's far out of the way from most of campus and the truck can be very slow
rw_title: so I use it to cheer myself up after a visit to the dental school. If you see the guy with food drooling out of his mouth eating a falafel platter

rw_comment: There's not much else I can say that hasn't already been said. Spicy, pricey burritos that come with a long wait but a fantastic flavor. The only thing to add is that they seriously have the best horchata in the city. Be sure to try it.

There's a reason the garbanzo beans taste like Indian food. The truck is owned by the Indians who own Lovash--across the street from Lucky's restaurant near 3rd and South. This truck is a pretty sad excuse for mexican, though if I'm stuck on spruce street they make an decent chocolate mole to dress the otherwise bland enchiladas.

The Indonesian lady running the cart shared her great Indonesian lunch with me one day and turned me onto the best Indonesian food spots in the city. Nowhere near campus, unfortunately. The reason the hot sauce is so hot? It's sambal--a southeast asian sauce. So if you like your Mexican food to somehow taste like Malaysian food, this is the place for you... I guess?! I tried to talk her into selling rendang or mee, please everyone keep asking and maybe we can convince her to convert to a solid southeast asian cart instead of fake mexican!!!
For $6.50, I got a huge veal stew crepe. It was great, the man was super nice and I can't wait to go back for lunch another time.
Not that bad. But don't ever try the Pad Thai!
All heat, no flavor.

The line is always pretty long, but you still will probably get your food faster than some of the other trucks in that row. That's also the downfall to Magic Carpet-- they don't actually make anything fresh. So while this is probably the truck I go to most often (it's convenient, great selection of good, awesome food you can't get at other trucks) the food is often just a little too mushy and flavorless. Make sure you get hot sauce with everything.

Many, many, many times better than the other Indian truck on campus. The portions are appropriate (indian food is heavy, this will fill you up) and the prices are great. You can get a good veggie curry and be filled up for 1/3 of the price of going to one of sit-down buffets on campus, even if those are a lot better. This is convenient, cheap, and tasty. My new favorite truck.

The food tastes pretty good, but the portions are tiny! They don't even fill up the whole bowl, and even if they did it would still be pretty small. The food at the other Indian food cart can last me for 2 meals, this isn't even enough for one. I think it depends on who is working there, because one person actually fills the bowls. The platters don't give you much more.

I just went there for the first time. I got the falafel feta pita sandwich -- by far the best one I've had on campus.  The ingredients were much fresher.  He must use locally grown tomatoes or something, because the tomatoes on my pita were better than anything I've found in groceries around here.  He was really friendly and obviously had good rapport with some regulars at the truck.  I just wish it was closer to the hospital where I work.
La Dominique's is like a glacier. It's substantial, but really slow.
I had their \chicken\" sandwich. I did not like it because the chicken was processed. Quite surprising. Most trucks as far as I know use real chicken. Memo's was the spongy fake stuff."
Lots of Vegetarian options and the best salsas and very cheap.  Order a burrito and expect to wait for them to grill it perfectly.  Friendly Cambodian refugees work here.
Their food is so good sometimes we come from Delaware back to our hometown of Philly just for their food.

All food is precooked unlike some other Chinese trucks in the city. My chicken was a little dry. The kung pao sauce was awful, way too sweet.
I miss my beloved Chinese truck in front of Drexel's Center City campus!!
This is the best mexican food I have ever eaten outside of Mexico.  For the money you get a delicious,nutritious fresh meal!!

After feeling a great displeasure from Lovash's downsized, minuscule portions, I needed another Indian food truck.  So I decided to try this one.  The portions are so much bigger!  Plus the food is just as tasty and also very spicy which is the way I like it.  There are three level of heats from mild to spicy, note that spicy is pretty damn spicy.  What makes it even better is that the food is cooked on the spot; it's piping hot when it gets to you.  Granted, the wait is a little long compared to other food trucks.  One thing to try is the mango drink.  Although full of flavor, it could be even better if it was icy cold but it still cools you down in the summer heat.  Contrary to some of the other reviews, I feel that the owner is generally friendly, smiling while greeting you.

My spinach pie was soggy and greasy and had a weirdly sweet flavor.  

The hummus is ok.  The falafel is kind of bland.  

This place doesn't really deserve the adoring throngs that line up every day.
Fastest food ever.  Food was basic with no extras, but good portion size.
Their breakfast tacos are amazing. Incredibly satisfying, and not a bad deal.

This is a great food cart.  Really nice guys, they move quickly through long lunch hour lines, and they make a huge variety of things.  My personal favorite is their grilled chicken pita with honey mustard, lettuce, tomato, and onions.  (It\\'s yummy, huge and filling, but also seems healthier than many regular food cart items.)  Other people in my department recommend their hot dogs, sausages, cheeseburgers and cheesesteaks.  This cart is very popular among people working in the Penn Science buildings, but it\\'s also extremely convenient if you have to make a trek over to Penn student health for any reason.  Definitely worth a try!

This is by far the freshest and best fruit cart on campus. I\\'ve tried them all, and none compare. Plus, the servings are larger here. The lady who runs this cart always makes the fruit salads to order, and packs extra fruit in the container. Highly recommended!
There is nothing special about this truck. It is very average in pretty much every way, including the name.
The Crepewalk now has a new guy running it, and he is doing a great job! He is extremely friendly and provides great food. The crepes are full to capacity and delicious, definitely an addiction! :)

Quite honestly you get what you pay for, and this truck has dirt cheap prices, but yuck fest food. I paid 3.00 for a Tofu/Broccoli fried rice plate, and got a LOT of food with gravy on it (my stomach felt horrible after eating). I must say the folks are really nice though! This truck may be good for some, but I wouldn't go here again, and I don't recommend it.

Coming back from ROTC stuff early in the morning and getting Khan's $2 sausageeggeandcheese saltpeppercatchup is the best part of my day. $2 come on man... that's amazing. He always gets my business because he is open nice and early. Also what seems like unfriendlyness I think is just awkwardness... and he probably doesnt speak english. One time my attractive girl indian friend walked by while I was waiting for a sandwich and he flipped out and said creepy things in half Pakistani. Quite a character. Also never give him any bill bigger than a 10. He might rob you. 

Sadly I think he is out of business. It's been almost two weeks since I saw him last.
The only time i eat here is if I don't want to buy McD's but besides that this is one of the worst chinese food I'd ever had!!!!  I mean how can you mess up chinese food you know?

This is one amazing find for me. He tries to make every crepe a work of art and all of them DELICIOUS. It's easy to notice that the quality of his ingredients are really high. All together an amazing find. Try the new tiramisu crepe, it's so gorgeous and tasty it deserves to be served in a nice restaurant.

HEALTHY for a food truck. If you start going there enough, the lady throws in an extra (excellent) falafel with your meal. Chicken platters are recommended especially.  Don't go to Yue Kee (which sucks), go here!

I actually enjoyed the food quite a lot. The masala was cooked well, the rice not so well but the spice made up for it. Its not cheap, but the portion is good and I prefer it to most of the Indian restaurants (except maybe New Delhi). Will definitely go again.

The hot dog with chili I got was as good as a hot dog can be and I only had to wait for a minute. I really was surprised to read all the reviews about his \unfriendly\" persona; he was very talkative. He even cracked a few jokes and asked for my name (and gave me his
rw_overall: but I didn't catch the first name-his last does seem to be Khan). Then again
rw_speed: so maybe he's just more relaxed. "

rw_comment: The food was OK, not very spicy and limited selection. Tiny portions for the price. Stick with Curry on Wheels.

1. Cheesesteak, eggs and cheese with ketchup
2. Hangover cure (sausage, ham, eggs and cheese)

Although Koja can sometimes take a while, it is still the best food truck on campus. They have a wide variety of Korean and Japanese items but they are most known for their Korean dishes. The Pork Bulgoki is AMAZING, but spicy and I also love their spicy tofu noodle platter. The Koja lady is very friendly, especially to regulars. If you are pressed for time, just call ahead! It's definitely a must-try on campus.
Bento Box is fantastic.  The fact that I can get Hibachi, sushi, and a drink for less than ten bucks is fantastic.  The fact they're across the street doesn't hurt.

Be aware that the menu here is out-dated.
The Mexican Sandwich is now $7
Where has she gone? I really really really miss this truch!
These guys are awesome! They always remember my order and get it made really quickly. Super-friendly and prices are so reasonable!
Fave food truck. Love Love Love! I always get bacon and egg whites on a bagel...she knows my order by heart!

My top picks are their curry chicken, delicious w moist chicken and potatos..seafood combo has crisp veggies, never overcooked.. and their hot and sour soup, so very tasty. You can order 2 choices of sauces.. garlic sauce or sweet and sour sauce for ur platters. I LOVE LOVE their garlic sauce. def quick cheap eats :)
Have had their spicy rice noodle with chicken many times, and bulgoki. It\\'s very good; the cooking time is very slow (not an in between classes meal) but worth it.

Lost track of them when they relocated from 30th and Market and thought I\\'d never see them again. Turns out they\\'ve been up on Spruce the whole time. My dad turned me onto them, and he\\'s no longer with us, but I always remember the places and things he taught me about.\\n\\nAnd this is one of them. Speed is slow, but what with long lines and the MASSIVE amount of food they put on your platter (generous is an understatement), it\\'s worth the wait. You can\\'t go wrong with whatever you purchase, but my personal favorite is jerk chicken with rice and beans. Mix that jerk sauce in with the rice and it\\'s simply amazing. I\\'ve been known to make both of my sides rice and beans just for that purpose.\\n\\nThey couple running the place have always been pretty sociable to me and mine, so I\\'m a bit surprised to find them rating so low on friendliness for some. A Gigi\\'s and Big R platter can last you a day, and satisfy you for far longer.

I always passed this cart because I saw Asian people running it, but I decided to try it today and am amazed at how good this is and how much food you get for your money. These are among the largest sandwiches you can get from a food cart. I got the Kefta with an extra grape leaf. Everything was fresh and tasty. The spicy sauce has a good kick to it. I will return!

When I order my falafel sandwich the man was very polite and nice. While he was making it he even gave me a fried falafel to munch on while i wait.  THIS WAS THE BEST FALAFEL I\\'D EVER PUT IN MY MOUTH.  He made the sandwich very quickly.
