The actual sandwich was delicious and succulent  filled with the freshest ingredients i\\'d ever  seen and a lunch truck. The tomatos were incredibly red and sweet (i don\\'t even like tomatos that much) fresh cilantro. and topped off with some amazing spicy sauce that is out of this world. I will be getting all my falafels from here from now on. GOODBYE HUMMUS. This lunch truck changed my life it will change yours too probably.

Ground beef biryani (with or without Rata)is a little different than other dish. The portion of it is usually 1.5 than other dish. Chicen Tikka Alu or Masala is the best among foodtrucks. It\\'s spicy I know, but it\\'s great for winter.

The speed it super-fast. They can take care 30 ppl in 5 minutes. Some ppl can get their food in less than 2 mintes. The price is also very cheap. The only problem of their food is that they are NOT tasty at all. Would only recommend to you when you have limit time and need some fast stuff not tasty stuff.

i work at a center city hotel so i called in, food was hot tasty and prepared the way i like it. i had the jerk chicken rice and beans, it was delicious. you have to be quite agressive when you order.ppl will cut in line. but this is philly, so i expected it.
Had beef lomein for lunch. It could have used some extra flavor...but overall it was pretty good. Having gone to a few other chinese and japanese trucks, this one has been the best.

I have been going to DD for years. I like the chicken egg foo young. They use dark meat chicken, which is very tender. I enjoy the gravy taste quite a bit. The egg foo young is deliciously deep fried. The only downside - once you\\'re done, this food will sit like a brick in your stomach.

I dream about this cart. There was a time in my life that I was eating here two-three times a week. I call ahead and order the spicy tofu noodles. The delicious spicy sauce soaks into the rice noodles and tofu on the grill. It is so filling, could easily be two meals, but the noodles don\\'t reheat well, so it\\'s an excuse to pig out and eat it all in one sitting. Sue is the sweetest lady. They don\\'t start taking phone calls for lunch orders until 11:45 am or so. It gives me spicy belly but it is worth it.
Avoid at all costs.

Tried the General Tsaos chicken and was EXTREMELY disappointed. A few bites in, I noticed a pungent odor as I lifted my fork. Either they mixed in fish (not pieces of white meat),  gizzard, or the meat was rotten - it was mushy with  dark spots throughout. I tried avoiding these pieces, but after another two bites I couldn\\'t take it any more and threw all of it out. Big waste!

The best Chinese food truck on campus, bar none. There are many average dishes here, but there are also a lot of quality ones like the Singapore Noodles, the Beijing Hot Noodles, and most of their Specials menu. A little tip if you don\\'t like the wait - if you like Pork Belly, Ribs in Black Bean Sauce, or Chicken Leg Rice, those prepared really fast, so you\\'ll often get your order before the people in front of you.

There are actually 4 levels:mild, medium, spicy and spicy hot. If you want to eat something that is meant to be spicy( unlike other foodtruckers who will ask you if you want some hot sauce, you know), get some food here. Chicken tikka Masala is fantastic. Ginger there is also very good. But the speed is very slow.

Best steaks I\\'ve had so far on campus, much heartier than Bui\\'s. Decent breakfast sandwiches, although I still prefer Bui. They generally run about 25-50 cents more than some other food carts, but the quality of the steaks makes it worth it.

Dishes are bland, unappealing, and downright gross. The sauces are thick and the vegetables taste old. Worse yet, the owners always seem angry and the wait is excruciating. Kim\\'s down the street is a much better meal for 1/5 the wait time.
I had a lamb gyro and it was terrific.  Tons of meat, yummy sauce and a good price.  I saw someone complain about the poor wrapping - I think it\\'s just because it was overflowing with food.  :-)

A great truck that isn\\'t that well known. \\n\\nAli Baba is still open.\\n\\nI highly recommend the special - usually couscous & chicken or the Kebee special - which is beef and rice. Very good each time.

Got the General Tso\\'s chicken.  Waited close to 20 minutes - clearly there was a problem with the General that day since 2 or 3 people ordered the same after me and were waiting as well.  Quality of the chicken was decent but the sauce didn\\'t even resemble General Tso\\'s sauce - more like soy sauce.
4 bucks for a footlong turkey hoagie? Sold. Nice guy too. He\\'s only one guy, so if he has a line it could take a while, but usually no more than 10 minutes.

I recommend going early since they can get backed up. Steak, egg, and cheese and the sausage, egg, and cheese are not to be missed. Pretty decent cheeseburgers and cheesesteaks too, and the hangover special is amazing. Bui\\'s sauce on EVERYTHING. Stay away from the spinach though, it\\'s kinda funky.

Fantastic cheese steak with low price and fast service. Since English is not their first language it is acceptable. If they speak better English then they are probably not there working seven days a week to serve us. So be nice and support them since they are not lucky like us to be in school. How many young hard-working couple you can count out there?

I\\'ve only eaten at the Gigi\\'s on 30th and Market street outside the train station.\\n\\nJerk Chicken is the best I\\'ve ever tasted.  Nice and spicy and not real sweet like some places.\\n\\nI always get the potato salad and collard greens as my 2 sides and both may be the best I\\'ve tasted.
LOVED the sweet potato taco - yum!!!

Their tacos aren\\'t tacos. All day I had been craving authentic tacos but when I opened my order it was fresher Taco Bell. Taco Bell does not make tacos, it puts some meat on a tortilla with lettuce and sour cream; Lucky\\'s does the same.
I love the shish tuok! There is another one that he serves periodically that I'm big into, but I can't remember the name. Awesome place if you like middle eastern food :).

I got the chicken teriyaki and I was disappointed - flavorless slightly sweet sauce, too much cabbage and mushy rice.  My boyfriend got the chicken sukiyaki, which was basically the same combo of cabbage, tofu and chicken with a different spicier sauce.  Spice, but not flavor.  The redeeming qualities of KoJa are the VERY friendly service and the white meat chicken.  I wish I got Chinese from down the block instead.

Got the Cowboy Steak after reading other positive reviews.  The meat was a little fatty in spots, there was way too much barbeque sauce on there destroying the taste of the meat, and worst of all, the cook seemed to forget to put ANY cheese on the cheesesteak.
Good portion for $6 ... until you taste it.  Horrible horrible food. Threw it out. Lovash serves much smaller portions but at least it\\'s good.
Small portions but better than most Indian restaurants in Philly.  Have to add the green sauce for any heat at all but that\\'s OK.
The food is average, but the service is below average and extremely rude at times and quite the turn off!
Vegetable lo mein is delicious. \\n\\nNot a huge fan of the chicken that is used for the chicken dishes.

They do not listen to the customer at all and have no combination options. The food tasted okay but was poorly made with undercooked veggies and \\'stir fried\\' meat that looked steamed with no caramelization. You get a lot of food for less than $5, but the quality suffers tremendously.

We got food to go at this truck while at the 2nd St Festival, It was late & they were very helpful helping me order & giving samplers  :) Everything was perfect, not a bite wasted. Best greens I\\'ve had in a long time, simply prep[ared. Excellent yams as well as the delicious jerk chicken, fish and fried chicken wings. Thank you!
I ordered the chicken and broccoli with white rice. It was amazing; especially if you mix the sauce with the rice. I\\'m drooling just thinking about it. I will definitely go again soon!

A thoroughly miserable experience. After ordering I waited 35 mins for my order to be processed, and given that they did not write down orders, regularly watched people receive food who ordered substantially after I did. The food itself (curry chicken platter) was swimming in oil but well cooked, served with mac\\'n\\'cheese which was very bland. The highlight was the rice which was tasty, albeit fluorescing from the \\'curry\\' oil. There was certainly plenty of food and I did not find the price as disconcerting as some. All told, not what I would have expected from the Vendy Cup winners.

This food truck is, by far, the worst I have encountered in Philly.  I waited 45 minutes to get my food while more pushy customers cut in line and received their orders before I got mine.  If you are going to actually order food, you must be aggressive, otherwise you will never eat.  I was hoping the food would be great after waiting so long, but the chicken was extremely oily and the mac and cheese is not as good as Wawa (and their\\'s isn\\'t great).  I also have to say that I can\\'t believe this truck won the Philly Vendy award.  There are a lot better food trucks in the area than this one.
Beef bulgoki was delicious - sauce and rice and beef were all great, price was good but not as great as some other ones ($6), but was very quick and delicious. so friendly and will definitely return!

Food is quite good; platters are large and quite filling.

Overall, compares quite well with other food trucks..don't understand the barrage of negative comments on here.
Only truck i've found that charges only 2.50 for a small with any kind of fruit you want. none of this \no melon\" business. definitely worth it!! "

I wasn\\'t sure how to rate convenience; I\\'m not one to eat on the go. How about taste? This stuff is good! Beef nachos with guac - the beef is tender and tastes terrific, guac is fresh and the right consistency. Portion more than enough. Not a steal, but well worth the $$.

Yummy, pretty falafel. It's green inside, because Memo uses fava beans, which he says is Egyptian style. Memo is so nice, and the ingredients are always fresh. Very convenient for us Drexel folks. Please review more trucks on Drexel campus!

I have to admit, the long lines every time I walked past made me keep walking. But, after reading some reviews, I decided to give it a try...I do love food, after all.

I was very surprised, even with the super long line, I didn't wait more than 10 minutes, and my order was put together in less than 1 minute.

I'm sure they have loads of great dishes, but I wanted to try something that I've never seen anything like before. So, I went with the seitan grinder. The flavor was nice, if a little bland (do not skip the hot sauce, it's not super hot and without it, the sandwich may have no flavor at all). And, the pita gets way too soggy. On the plus side, the veggies inside were very nice, warmed through but not mushy.(If you've never had it before, seitan is made from wheat gluten and looks a lot like roast beef. The flavor is very mild, hardly even noticeable with the other flavors of the sandwich and mostly masked by the sesame seeds they put on it.)

The food is difficult, no impossible, to eat, though. I'm glad I took mine home because I emptied the contents of my pita and ate it more like a salad with pita bread on the side. The flimsy, little plastic forks really don't help all that much. I wouldn't recommend getting a sandwich here if you've got somewhere to go afterward...you'll probably end up with it all over your shirt.

All that said, I'd definitely recommend it, but I wouldn't make it a daily stop.
It's the best Chinese truck in this area. Their General Tao's chicken is awesome. The only bad thing is the owner has never smiled!
delicious. sanitary (one person handles the money, the other handles the food). love it.
authentic dishes from the Chinese menu. would recommend less salt for better health.
good quality food.  $8 for a steak burrito, I thought was a bit expensive for truck food.

I had Chicken Teriyaki with Lomien. The Teriyaki sauce was awesome. 

The owner is very friendly. 

The only downside that it closes so fast. If you go there after 4 pm, there would be only few menus left for you to order.

I had General Tso Chicken today and it was great. Freshly-fried tender chicken and awesome sauce. Its sauce might be too salty for someone but I love it.

If you could ignoring how long you have to wait, this is a good place to go!

So I'm giving 5 stars for the Indonesian special she serves every Thursday.  It's incredible and so convenient in the veritable wasteland of culinary joys that is 33rd.  On a normal day, I'll get a chicken tostada, which tastes nothing like Mexican food but is great when approached as its own unique dish.
Simply delicious!

I frequent this cart at least once a week and I have to say, for the price you can\\'t beat the amount of food you get. It\\'s no gourmet restaurant but its quick and hits the spot. Plus the lady who runs the cart is really friendly. My favorite cart around campus by far!

I love this place! The food is cheap, and it's a great lunch. Lots of options if you  want to try something new. Sure, the eggplant parm is great, but I also love the chicken gyro and the Italian sausage works. I think it'd be pretty awkward to eat these during class, though, the gyro is stuffed with lettuce and tomatoes (a good thing!) and the Isw is very saucy. 

Lyn and Quan are always friendly, and always smiling. There are always a lot of people there, so sometimes if you are in a rush, it's not the best place to go, but the service isn't at all slow. If you're one of 3 people there, you'll get your food in no time! If you're one of 10...don't go when you're rushing to class.

Overall, Lyn's is awesome!!!
I always go and get the chicken falafel sandwich for 5 dollars. Its open all the time which is definitely a plus.

I have been to this truck twice. The food is really great. I've had the coconut chicken crepe (tasty), and the Mexican crepe (spicy). They were both large quantities, and almost couldn't finish them, but had to cuz it was SOO GOOD! It might be expensive but you are paying for the quality of ingredients.
Again, it has a lot of Chinese food in it also at this location
awesome and the hemo sauce was great

Tried out a burrito earlier today. The food was good and the ingredients were fresh but I don\\'t understand why everyone thinks this place is 5 star. Definitely better than Taco Bell. And I will definitely give it a seconnd chance.
It has a lot of Chinese food: Seitan is actually Mianjin from China;Anything related to Tofu like Magic meatball Foochow etc are of course from China. Mc-\\\Manchu\\\"
rw_overall: Manchu is a ethnic minority of China...I believe the genre of this good truck should be at least part of Chinese. Tempeh is from Japan though."

rw_comment: I\\'m from New Mexico so I am REALLY picky about Mexican food.  This place is the best. trust me.
tons of well cooked food for a relatively inexpensive price. a college kids dream!
I am Indian and have never tasted such horrible Indian food. The vegetarian curry was bland, tasteless with lot of water with some turmeric and curry powder.\\nI am never going here again.
tons of well cooked food for a relatively inexpensive price. a college kids dream!

They work real fast! I went there at 6 pm. There were 2 people in line before me. I waited less than 10 min to got my order.

My Kung-Pao pork was tasteless but the size was bigger than i expected (for$4).
Best tacos in West Philly.  Pastor is fantastic.  The wait can be excessive.
The crispy chicken and grilled chicken are pretty good!the price very low,the cashier so friendly

Is the food great? No. But it\\'s decent and satisfying. The owners are friendly, hard-working people trying to make an honest living and I enjoy being a patron. My personal favorite is the sesame chicken. If you want a simple dish, the quality is not much worse than places you will pay double. For the fancier stuff, I wouldn\\'t recommend it. $4.50 for a meal is a great bargain

This average is based on 12 month hits collection.Low/Medium/High denotes the competition for this keyword. Choose any High competition keyword and search it in google you will see that first 10-20 result are from High Rank Sites and their article is highly optimized for that keyword so you will face a tight competition for that keyword (if you write an article using that keyword).Best guideline is use keywords which is having Low competition and reasonable monthly search count (let 1000 count per month). As competition is low for that keyword so chance of getting ranked in first page will be high.

I do not think that you can separate the litlte thing from the big thing when it comes to conveying messages.  I mean if one is in a professional environment, the whole environment projects professionalism, care, attention to detail, and most importantly attention to the patient.Esprit de corps creates professionalism and styles of behavior and concern which makes the patient feel at ease in a difficult situation.I also think that one should not use the white coat or the gloves to make the patient feel that the situation is more complicated than it is.  Some informality is important especially in take home instructions.  Common sense is too.  Obviously, infection control and hygiene are critical.But I remember diagnosing a tuberculosis infected HIV infected physician.  The physician was clearly in denial.  He was seeing patients while coughing and losing weight.He coughed up a sixteen ounce cup of sputum during his visit with me.  I was afraid that I would convert my PPD since we did not do the protocol of isolation and UV light immediately.  But, on the other hand, I decided to do everything in the clinic before he went to the ward.  We got a microscopic sputum diagnosis of AFB before he left his cubicle.  That simplified his work up on the floor and he was immediately sent to where he needed to be.  Working in an inner city hospital, I was told when entering the patient\\'s room by the supervisory physician that he did not believe in the physician\\'s weight loss and symptoms.The important thing is to listen to the patient and address the medical issue at hand.  Messages are important but only part of the picture.  Even mistakes can lead to positive results if one addresses the patient respectfully.  I remember a thirty something patient coming in for a flu shot in a year that there was a scarcity and the indications were for people over sixty five and with extraordinary conditions.  This patient looked healthy and I immediately told him that he looked too healthy to get a flu shot.  He took off his hat and he had an IV line in place for chemotherapy for a brain tumor.  So, I congratulated him on well he looked under the circumstances and that he had fooled me; the patient was pleased even though I had clearly spoken too quickly.Perhaps, the point that brings these two cases to mind is that the intention of the doctor conveys the message as well as the natural symbolism.  The unexpected can happen at any moment.  One should first worry about what needs to be done and do to right by the patient rather than simply worry about the impression.Bohdan A Oryshkevich, MD, MPH
